Financial inclusion in Tanzania has introduced multifaceted opportunities to improve financial accountability, transparency in governance as well as transparency in other economic sectors.

Curtis Ingersoll and Alex Cuff have developed a detailed analysis of the impact, benefits from electronic money as well as the challenges seen in mainstreaming. In moneyFor, Alex Cuff and Curtis Ingersoll share the USE of State account balances in Tanzania to test program interventions in the context of the Social Accountability for Services.

For these interests to materialize, citizens need information in a convenient, timely format that they immediately digest. Digital technology is a big step towards that and the public and private sectors in Tanzania have recognized that.

There many mobile money promotions out there because of how truly revolutionary it still is and the public/private sector have to work together to make this happen. When this happens, the public and private sector both gain from this partnership.

This partnership is not anything new. the public and private sector have historically worked together and made big differences. For state account balances to benefit the Tanzanian Populationlong run, a public-private partnership that focuses on approaches to broaden the uptake of digital technologies, like mobile money and electronic vouchers is needed.
